04054nam a22006855i 9781400845316DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20122012nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008453167 a10.1515/97814008453162doi  a(DE-B1597)453851  a(OCoLC)979905329  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aPHI0000002bisacsh1 aGoodin, Robert E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOn Settling /cRobert E. Goodin.  aCourse Book 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2012] 4cÂ©2012  a1 online resource (128 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tone. Modes of Settling -- ttwo. The Value of Settling -- tthree. What Settling Is Not -- tfour. Settling in Aid of Striving -- tConclusions -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn a culture that worships ceaseless striving, "settling" seems like giving up. But is it? On Settling defends the positive value of settling, explaining why this disdained practice is not only more realistic but more useful than an excessive ideal of striving. In fact, the book makes the case that we'd all be lost without settling--and that even to strive, one must first settle. We may admire strivers and love the ideal of striving, but who of us could get through a day without settling? Real people, confronted with a complex problem, simply make do, settling for some resolution that, while almost certainly not the best that one could find by devoting limitless time and attention to the problem, is nonetheless good enough. Robert Goodin explores the dynamics of this process. These involve taking as fixed, for now, things that we reserve the right to reopen later (nothing is fixed for good, although events might always overtake us). We settle on some things in order to concentrate better on others. At the same time we realize we may need to come back later and reconsider those decisions. From settling on and settling for, to settling down and settling in, On Settling explains why settling is useful for planning, creating trust, and strengthening the social fabric--and why settling is different from compromise and resignation. So, the next time you're faced with a thorny problem, just settle. It's no failure.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aCompromise (Ethics). 0aContentment. 0aPHILOSOPHYvGeneral. 0aPOLITICAL SCIENCEvGeneral. 0aPolitical ethics. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978140084531640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400845316423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400845316.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK